'''William Joseph Kayatta Jr.''' (born October 27, 1953) is a [[United States federal judge|United States Circuit Judge]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit]].

== Early life and education ==
Kayatta was born in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]], [[Rhode Island]] in 1953. He earned a bachelor's degree in 1976 from [[Amherst College]] and then earned a law degree in 1979 from [[Harvard Law School]].<ref name=wh>White House: [http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2012/01/23/president-obama-nominates-two-serve-us-court-appeals "President Obama Nominates Two to Serve on the US Court of Appeals," January 23, 2012], accessed June 5, 2012</ref> After law school, he served as a law clerk for Judge [[Frank M. Coffin]] of the United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit from 1979 to 1980.<ref>''Bangor Daily News'': [http://bangordailynews.com/2009/12/08/news/judge-lawmaker-frank-coffin-dies/ Judy Harrison, "Judge, lawmaker Frank Coffin dies," December 8, 2009], accessed June 5, 2012</ref>

== Professional career ==
In 1980, Kayatta joined the [[Portland, Maine]], law firm Pierce Atwood LLP as an associate.<ref name=wh /> He became partner in 1986 and has focused his practice on complex trial and appellate litigation.<ref name=wh /> He also has argued two cases before the [[Supreme Court of the United States]].<ref name=wh /> In 2010, he served as the lead investigator for the American Bar Association committee that reviewed the qualifications of Supreme Court nominee Elena Kagan.<ref>''Portland Press Herald'': [http://www.pressherald.com/news/portland-lawyer-leads-panel-reviewing-kagan_2010-07-03.html Trevor Maxwell, "Portland lawyer leads panel reviewing Kagan," July 3, 2010], accessed June 5, 2012</ref> In April 2011, the Supreme Court of the United States appointed him to serve as special master in an interstate water-rights dispute, ''Kansas v. Nebraska and Colorado''.<ref>Maine News Simply: [http://www.mainenewssimply.com/content/supreme-court-appoints-attorney-william-j-kayatta-jr-special-master Supreme Court Appoints Attorney William J. Kayatta, Jr. as Special Master," April 5, 2011], accessed June 5, 2012</ref>

He has served as president of the Maine Bar Foundation.<ref>Maine News Direct: [http://www.themaineswitch.com/release.html?id=732 Pierce Atwood's Kayatta Elected President," April 15, 2004], accessed June 5, 2012</ref>
In 2010, the Maine Bar Foundation presented him with the Howard H. Dana Award for his career-long pro bono efforts on behalf of low-income Maine citizens.<ref>''Portland Press Herald'': [http://www.pressherald.com/archive/lawyers-told-volunteering-to-help-poor-more-critical_2010-01-21.html Trevor Maxwell, "Lawyers told volunteering to help poor more critical," February 26, 2010], accessed June 5, 2012</ref> He has also received special recognition awards from the Disability Rights Center of Maine, the Maine Equal Justice Partners, and the Maine Children's Alliance for his pro bono representation of disabled Maine children.<ref>Maine Forecaster: [http://www.theforecaster.net/content/pnms-kayatta-appointment-0 Amy Anderson, "Obama picks southern Maine lawyer for federal appeals court," January 24, 2012], accessed June 5, 2012</ref> Kayatta is also a former Chair of the Professional Ethics Commission for Maine lawyers.

== Nomination to First Circuit ==
On January 23, 2012, President Obama nominated Kayatta to serve as a judge on the United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit.<ref name=wh /> He received a hearing before the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]] on March 14, 2012,<ref>''Portland Press Herald'': [http://www.pressherald.com/news/court-nominees-hearing-goes-very-smoothly_2012-03-15.html "U.S. circuit-court nominee's hearing goes 'very smoothly'," March 15, 2012], accessed June 5, 2012</ref> and his nomination was reported to the floor on April 19, 2012, by voice vote, with [[Jeff Sessions|Senator Sessions]] and [[Mike Lee (U.S. politician)|Senator Lee]] recorded as voting no.<ref>''Portland Press Herald'': [http://www.pressherald.com/news/senate-panel-endorses-kayatta-for-judgeship_2012-04-20.html Ann S. Kim, "Senate panel endorses Kayatta for judgeship," April 20, 2012], accessed June 5, 2012</ref>

Kayatta's confirmation hearing before the Senate Judiciary Committee was uncontroversial.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. circuit-court nominee's hearing goes 'very smoothly'| last=Riskind| first=Jonathan| url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/court-nominees-hearing-goes-very-smoothly_2012-03-15.html|accessdate=16 August 2012|newspaper=Portland Press Herald|date=15 March 2012}}</ref> His nomination needed only confirmation by the full Senate, but the process was stalled by [[Republican Party (United States)|GOP]] [[filibuster]]s for a series of tactical reasons, such as to block the consideration of another of President Obama's judicial appointments, [[Robert E. Bacharach]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lisa|first=Mascaro |title=Senate GOP blocks popular judicial nominee, halts confirmations|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-senate-gop-blocks-popular-judicial-nominee-halts-confirmations-20120730,0,2974229.story|accessdate=16 August 2012|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=30 July 2012}}</ref> With the adjournment of the Senate session on January 2, 2013, the nomination expired.

On January 3, 2013, he was renominated to the same office.<ref>{{cite web|title=President Obama Re-nominates Thirty-Three to Federal Judgeships, January 3, 2013|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/01/03/president-obama-re-nominates-thirty-three-federal-judgeships |publisher=whitehouse.gov|accessdate=February 7, 2013}}</ref> On February 7, 2013, the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]] reported his nomination to the floor by voice vote, with Senator [[Jeff Sessions]] recorded as a no vote.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kayatta judicial nomination bound for Senate floor vote|url=http://www.theforecaster.net/news/print/2013/02/07/kayatta-judicial-nomination-bound-senate-floor-vot/150430|accessdate=February 7, 2013|newspaper=The Forecaster (Maine)|date=February 7, 2013}}</ref> The Senate confirmed his nomination on February 13, 2013, by a vote of 88 ayes to 12 nays.<ref>[https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=113&session=1&vote=00020 Senate Roll Call]</ref> He received his commission on February 14, 2013.<ref>[http://www.fjc.gov/servlet/nGetInfo?jid=3458&cid=999&ctype=na&instate=na Biographical Directory of Federal Judges]</ref>  Kayatta will fill the seat vacated by Judge [[Kermit Lipez]], who took [[senior status]] at the end of 2011.<ref>''Portland Press Herald'': [http://www.pressherald.com/news/Signs-favorable-for-.html "Maine on the Hill: Signs favorable for Cape Elizabeth nominee to appeals court," March 11, 2012], accessed June 5, 2012</ref>

== Personal ==
Kayatta lives in [[Cape Elizabeth, Maine]]. His wife is Anne Swift-Kayatta.

